  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much money can I deposit in my account?",
  "response": "The amount of money you can deposit into your account depends on several factors, including the type of account, the bank's policies, and any legal or regulatory limits. Here are some key considerations:\n\n1. **Bank Policies**:  \n   - Most banks allow you to deposit any amount into your account, but they may have internal thresholds for reporting or monitoring large deposits.  \n   - Some accounts (e.g., savings or certificates of deposit) may have maximum limits on how much you can deposit.  \n\n2. **Legal Reporting Requirements**:  \n   - In many countries, banks are required to report cash deposits exceeding a certain amount to regulatory authorities. For example:  \n     - In the **U.S.**, cash deposits over **$10,000** must be reported to the IRS via a **Currency Transaction Report (CTR)**.  \n     - In the **EU**, similar reporting requirements exist, though thresholds vary by country.  \n   - Depositing slightly less than the reporting threshold to avoid reporting (called \"structuring\") is illegal and can result in penalties.  \n\n3. **Account Type**:  \n   - Checking and savings accounts typically have no strict deposit limits, but high-yield savings accounts or specialized accounts may have restrictions.  \n   - Business accounts may have higher limits compared to personal accounts.  \n\n4. **Currency and Payment Method**:  \n   - Cash deposits may have stricter limits compared to electronic transfers or checks.  \n   - Some banks may limit the amount you can deposit via ATMs or mobile deposit.  \n\n5. **Tax Implications**:  \n   - Large deposits may trigger scrutiny from tax authorities, especially if the source of funds is not clearly documented.  \n\nTo ensure compliance and avoid issues, it\u2019s best to check with your bank directly for their specific deposit limits and policies. If you're depositing a large amount, be prepared to provide documentation about the source of the funds.",
